📂 1. ls – List Files
•	Use: Show files and folders in the current directory.
•	Example:
ls
Shows: file1.txt myfolder script.sh
________________________________________
📁 2. cd – Change Directory
•	Use: Move into another folder (directory).
•	Example:
cd myfolder
________________________________________
📄 3. touch – Create a New File
•	Use: Create an empty file.
•	Example:
touch newfile.txt
________________________________________
📝 4. cat – View or Combine Files
•	Use: Show file content, or combine files.
•	Example:
cat file.txt
________________________________________
🛠️ 5. mkdir – Make Directory
•	Use: Create a new folder.
•	Example:
mkdir myfolder
________________________________________
❌ 6. rm – Remove Files or Folders
•	Use: Delete files or folders.
•	Example:
rm file.txt
rm -r myfolder  # for folders
________________________________________
✏️ 7. nano or vi – Edit Files
•	Use: Open a text file in editor.
•	Example:
nano file.txt
________________________________________
🔍 8. grep – Search Text in Files
•	Use: Search for a word inside files.
•	Example:
grep "main" program.c
________________________________________
📌 9. chmod – Change File Permissions
•	Use: Give read/write/execute permissions.
•	Example:
chmod +x script.sh
________________________________________
🧾 10. ps – Show Running Processes
•	Use: Show which programs are running.
•	Example:
ps
________________________________________
🔁 11. fork() – (System Call)
•	Use in OS Lab: Create a new process.
•	Example (C Code):
fork();  // creates a child process
